      <body>
        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0543.jpg" n="part4_p069.jpg" xml:id="img_0069" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p069.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_69_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>-la¬
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>But this principle of justice is not something which stands BES apE love, or AGAINST love.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>Love is not something ADDED to this principle of justice, but love IS, in its STRUTURE,
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>this principle of justice.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>Let me give an example for this. I know people who have a great desire
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>to sacrifice themselves, in the relationship to somehow else. They do not justice to themselves,
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>and in not doing justice to themselves, they don't do justice to the other one either: They
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>&amp; produce a relationship of (mutualngic) self-surrender, which Erich Fromm has called aGymbiötic
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>exploiting the other by submissivess in terms
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/> relationship, in which the one is actually
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>himself and to the other one. But where there is not justice, there may be
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>of lack of justice to
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>cha Stic self-surrender, buturrender mit cesdicetos self-surrender is not love. And so, we can repeat: this middle
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_14" n="N014"/>realm, which can also be called the realm of justice, is the realm in which love finds its structure.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_1_tl_15" n="N015"/>But now, where will we know about these structure? And here I answer: not by
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_69_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>natural law (we discussion that) in the sense of the Catholic authoritarian form; but we find it insofa¬
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>by natural law, as it belong to the very nature of man in his essential structure, to be a subject and
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>object of love, and therefore of those structureal elements of justice which are presupposed in every
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>act of love. In this sense we can use, without the authoritarian element, the doctrine of the natural
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>law. But if we don't use the authoritarian element, which the Roman Church uses, how can we know
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>about the comnands of natural law, or about the structure of justice—which is the same.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>And there my answer isbringing, and the word wisdom is a congressic term. Wisdom is
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>H. Schaef
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>CONQUERED by experience. Wisdom is not given by command. This experience is personal,
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>but it is first of all a collective experience of mankind.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_69_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>So we can say: The Ten Commandments, for instance, are not commandments which
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>can be applied as laws, but are the result of praematic experiences in which the structure of love
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>has come to consciousness of human brings. They are matters of wisdom. And therefore they
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>are in themselves not conconditional. None of the Ten Commandments—except the first, namely the
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>-7-
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>dʼune manière beaucoup de nouveau
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>de ses
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>de mon frere.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_9" n="N009"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_10" n="N010"/>cʼest avec un autre
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_11" n="N011"/>Monsieur M.
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_12" n="N012"/>de ses
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_13" n="N013"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_14" n="N014"/>dʼun autre
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_15" n="N015"/>de ses
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_16" n="N016"/>dans le
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_17" n="N017"/>dʼagiré
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_18" n="N018"/>Monsieur,
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_19" n="N019"/>Monsieur,
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_20" n="N020"/>dʼadresse à
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_21" n="N021"/>de votre beau et de
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_22" n="N022"/>dʼun autre
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_23" n="N023"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_24" n="N024"/>cʼest en lʼauteur de ses autres
               <lb facs="#facs_69_tr_3_tl_25" n="N025"/>dʼune manière
            </p>
            
